# Branch Naming Conventions

## Format

```
<type>/<short-description>
```

## Types

| Prefix | Use case |
|---|---|
| `feat/` | New features |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes |
| `refactor/` | Code refactoring |
| `docs/` | Documentation changes |
| `style/` | Formatting, code style |
| `test/` | Adding or updating tests |
| `chore/` | Build tasks, dependency updates |
| `perf/` | Performance improvements |

## Description rules

- Lowercase letters and hyphens only (kebab-case)
- 2–4 words, concise but descriptive
- Examples: `feat/i18n-strings`, `fix/websocket-reconnection`, `refactor/settings-screen`

## Generation process

1. Analyze changed files to determine the primary change type.
2. Identify the main feature or area affected (scope).
3. Compose: `<type>/<scope>-<description>`.
4. Check uniqueness: `git branch -a | grep <branch-name>`.
